text: here's a dumb thing that's made me more excited for this film. the colour grading is SO MUCH BETTER than the last trailer? okay. here me out! I was afraid after civil war... because the colour grading in that film was fuckin hot garbage okay? it just wasnt visually interesting and the whole airport fight isnt fun to watch after the first time... and that's mainly due to colours, there's no heavy contrasts and no use of warms or cools, it's all very in the middle... grey on grey on grey and nothing much else. no deep colours and shadows and hues in the darks or higher lights with hints of colours.. nothing!!  the first teaser for spider-man was like this too.. it looked boring and dull and bland in its colours and it made me worried for marvel films... THEN I SAW THE TRAILERS FOR GOTG!! and I was like 'LOOK HOW GOOD JAMES GUN IS WITH COLOURS' and then I see what taika is doing with thor.... and I was like: 'surely they can't be sticking with the shit civil war colours for homecoming.....'  and now THIS TRAILER!!! dude the colours!!! its so slight but it's so effective and the highs are golden and really pretty, there's way more contrast in the colours and you have interesting colours in the lows and everything!!! its such a simple change but it made me happy because i hate the look of civil war with a passion...  if you don't believe me, look at the webwings shit from the first teaser and compare it to this!! it looks great now!

text: Officially hyped!  Looks like a great original story, without the origin; which is utterly unnecessary at this point. I think this trailer gave a bit too much away about the narrative of the film, in terms of how the story progresses. However, the idea of Spider-Man having already been well established (5 movies in 12 years will do that for a guy) is where this movie seems to start from. In fact he starts at his peak: He has a custom suit, tailored by bloody Iron Man; he knows the Avengers and has gone toe-to-toe with half of them; and he has a massive social media fan-base!  Then some stuff goes down with Michael Keaton's 'Vulture' and a boat full of people; which Spider-Man (with his sweet-as, techie-gizmo suit) thinks he can handle. Turns out Vulture ain't no jobber, and wrecks the boat's day. Iron Man shows up and saves everybody, because he has also been in 5 movies, and only needed one origin story. He chews out Spider-Man for being a stupid, cocky idiot and not calling him, when he is literally in the same city, WHAT ARE YOU DOING?! He takes the suit back and now Peter is back to looking like he did, when he fought the Ultimate Warrior; back in 2002.  He then has to mess up Vulture's day, to prove to himself (and everyone) that he can he is still Avenger material; even after the whole emo Tobey Maguire phase. There a fight on a plane; because that's realistically the only way he can fight someone that can fly higher than the skyline. He, presumably, saves the day (Hooray!) and Stark is willing to let him join the club.

text: So ive seen so many fanboys and haters commenting about showing spoilers and stuff. DUDE thats what a trailer is these days! A trailer is not a summary you read behind yhe blu ray dvd you buy. A trailer is a showcase of the shorten route of storyline its gonna go, cinematography and vfx its going to include and in some cases( civil final trailer) a guest surprise character where everyone goes HOLY CRAP its partly both marketing and how the whole drill goes. Maybe some will complain how back in 80's or 90's they don't need to do this and they gross millions and more comparing to their budget. Just so you know, even stsr wars a box office phenomenon had a huge risk flopping. Firstly it wasn't a trend, second it had high budget and a lot of post production support in technicalities it was a big surprise back then even the way they commercialize the first film was just decent due to insufficient funds. Marvel who is now own by disney which is one of the big companies today ruling yours and every kid's parent's wallet has mastermind business leaders planned out every detail on selling their product to you. Showing a trailer of spoilers will not hinder but instead rise up their sales tremendously thanks to supporters and those who are dumb enough to go watch it to prove a point on how this will spoil the whole movie. Not generalizing everyone but those who don't know crap about the industry to yourself a favor and learn or read about it before making a fool out of yourself

text: Come on, seriously? Trailers are meant to get you excited for movies, not give away all the main plot points and show issues get resolved for heaven's sake. This trailer gave away WAY too much, and people that say it didn't must have used practically 0% of their imagination.They literally showed how the boat scene gets resolved! That was like the main event of the last trailer and teaser!! WHY? I don't blame Marvel as much as I blame the trailer house that edited this, but dang. For example, the first Jurassic Park movie's trailer didn't even show a dinosaur, yet it went on to be one of the most iconic movies of all time. Movies are supposed to be an adventure/a thrill ride, not a posed set of questions with only one left to be answered. Trailers like these are ruining the excitement of movies. It's hard for me to justify watching more than teasers these days, because at least I can go into the theater with the slightest bit of curiosity.

text: Looking at this trailer i can tell a couple of things and already it comes out straight away we're dealing with a spiderman we have never seen in his own feature length film before (Civil War don't count). Next off we're dealing with a villain that has an alternate motif and we haven't seen a movie adaptation of Vulture before.  It's brilliant that it isn't going to be easy for this spiderman. He's the hot-headed teenager that wants to be like every other superhero. We're finally getting the Spiderman we deserve. This isn't going to be our run of the mill, 'Kill Uncle Ben, Have a Funeral, Move on, Get bit by a spider, become Spiderman, rest of story, ETC'.  Marvel have never deliberately done a bad job of a film and no production company is perfect Marvel and Disney included. What they're giving us now is the outline to a story. An idea of what were setting ourselves up for. Just like every other big blockbuster.

text: Well, that has me sold, even more so than the first (epic) trailer did. Tony's going through some serious issues...you can see the loss of The Avengers -- and his complementing relationship w/ Steve Rogers -- is really affecting him...I wonder, on the timeline, how far along this tale takes place post-Civil War. A great set-up for when Thanos comes a killin'. Again, Keaton looks like he's going to eat up EVERY scene he's in in this film...this seems the perfect ironic/yet somewhat similar flipside of the Batman character...this guy seems like a sympathetic anti-hero/villain (like Loki?) w/ a purpose and a reason for his actions. I wonder if Keaton may get an Oscar (win?) nomination for Best Supporting Actor in this, cause his portrayal, from these nuggets, seems like some of his best work. Marvel, I think you've done it (yet) again.

text: To people who keep saying 'I've seen the whole movie by watching the trailer', grow up. What do you expect, this is a superhero movie and in most superhero MCU movies, the plot is simple. Hero goes through trauma, gets powers or abilities and becomes superhero, new threat rises, hero battles threat and loses round one, loses confidence and gives up, only to have his faith restored and fights the threat again and wins. Average superhero plot marvel uses all the time. This trailer shows this give or take. The only thing we find out is Stark intervenes in the boat scene and helps Spider-Man, before taking his suit because he disobeyed him. Hell, I had that already guessed from the first trailer. If you have the whole story people, answer me these questions? Does Spider-Man successfully land the plane on his own? Does Stark help him? Does Spider-Man take on shocker and Vulture single handedly? What happens to Shocker and Vulture at the end of the film? Do they die or will they live and reappear in the future? How does Spider-Man even defeat two villains teaming on him? What is Vulture's goal in this movie? Is it to kill Stark or destroy his legacy or is it even both? Is there an ulterior motive? Does Peter really get the girl in the end or does he ditch his homecoming date Liz Allen to save the day Spidey style like in the comics? What makes his homecoming dance so significant to the film's plot? Will any other Avengers' guess star in this movie. Is J.Jonah Jameson is this movie? What is Flash Thompson like in the movie? What easter eggs are there? Just a small amount of questions I came up with. This trailer shows us just enough to get an idea of the plot of the film and give us a taster of what to expect. Don't nitpick when there really isn't anything to nit pick about. CGI may not be up to scratch but the film is about 3 months off yet, so it's not like this is the final product.

text: So people are arguing about how much this trailer shows of the movie. It doesn't show everything, but it shows a lot.  In the last trailer it ends with a cliffhanger about that boat scene, now in this trailer we know the result of that scene. Which is pretty bad marketing in my opinion. It would've been great to see the movie and watch that scene without knowing the outcome. Knowing the outcome of that scene takes away from the experience and overall will make my viewing experience not as enjoyable. Something similar happened last year with Civil War and the scene where War Machine gets injured. I knew the outcome, so it took away emotion from the actual movie. Also we see that Stark asks Peter for the suit back which is another kinda large spoiler in the sense that it's probably the high point of a character arch that spider man will go through in this movie. Although we don't see the result of this arch in the trailer, we see event causes problems for our character, which is a HUGE part of a character arch.  Overall it's a pretty revealing trailer, and Marvel should seriously stop doing this with their movies.

text: People who sniffed at Stark saying "If you're nothing without the suit, you shouldn't have it" need to rewatch all MCU films. They all convey the same message: "it is not your superpower but who you are as a person that defines you."  Iron Man villains are usually his own designs but in the wrong hands. The trilogy basically can be summed up to: it is the pilot instead of the suit what makes one a hero or a villain. Rogers was chosen as Cap because of his courage and integrity, not because of his amazing combat skills, that he had none. Thor was born with great powers but Mjolnir only chose him when he learnt about humility and responsibility for his people.  Now that the first MCU hero Stark is passing on this message to the next generation and all people are saying is that it's ironic?

text: I really can't understand why those so-called "true Spider-Man fans" are so antagonistic towards people who liked Sam Raimi's films and Tobey Maquire's Spider-Man. Second, you all are hypocrites. You all say that if the character is not like in the comics, then it's bad, but, you also all love Robert Downey Jr. as Iron Man, who is very different from the comic book Tony Stark, that was humorless, downbeat, and super, SUPER serious all the time. text: Questions that have yet to be answered: - Are we ever going to hear about Uncle Ben? - Does Peter get the same suit back at the end of the film? - Is Zendaya actually Mary Jane? - Does Ned keep Peter's secret? - Does Peter defeat the Vulture? - Does Iron Man or anyone else help Peter defeat the Vulture? - What's the Shocker's role in this story exactly? - Does Peter go to the Homecoming dance? - What is Liz Allen's role in this story exactly? - What is Zendaya's character's role in this story exactly? - Why haven't we seen Flash Thompson even though he's been confirmed for the movie? - Does Vulture take someone that Peter cares about hostage? - Does anyone die? - Does Peter become an Avenger? - Does Aunt May start dating Tony Stark? - Is the Daily Bugle involved in the story? - Is there anyone who works at the Daily Bugle involved in the story? - Do we get any hints about the Osborn family in this story? - What other Spider-Man villains exist in this universe? - What happens to that plane that Peter is trying to save? - Does Vulture actually have a family or is he just talking about his friends? - What's the deal with those bank robbers with the Chitauri weapons from the last trailer?  Questions that have in fact been answered: - Does Peter get his Spidey suit privileges taken away by Uncle Tony? Yes. - Does anyone find out Peter's identity? Yes.

text: The reasons Spiderman has had three reboots in the past 15 years is because of film complications during production of the sequels. First, it all started in 1996 when Marvel almost went bankrupt, in an era to save the company, Stan Lee decided to sell the Spiderman Film Rights to Sony Productions. This saved the Marvel Company from becoming bankrupt, and Sony later made three Spiderman movies starring Tobey Maguire, in a rush to make the fourth sequel, the company couldn't agree on a strong plot that’s when Sony cancelled the Spiderman franchise. In later years during 2012, Sony thought that they might give Spidey another chance, and that’s when they made the Amazing Spiderman movies with Andrew Garfield. After the second Amazing Spiderman sequel crashed and burned in the box office, Sony decided to cancel it again. Marvel at this point had already set up the MCU and was begging Sony to let Spiderman join their MCU. After lots of planning, Sony and Marvel decided to share Spidey and thus now letting Marvel add him a new spot in the MCU.

text: I'm genuinely sad that they didn't decide to find a way to introduce Garfield's SpiderMan in the MCU. I know a lot of people didn't like AMS2, but it could have worked.   I like that Andrew's SpiderMan made his own suit. That showed genius and that we was frugal with what cash he had. Also IronMan made the Iron Spider Suit, now if we get to see that ever, it's not gonna be as special.  I like that what could be called the "Gwen Stacey Arc" had ended, we could have moved on to a new chapter in his career.  I like that we had established villains already. Hobgoblin, Electro, Rhino, plus the rest of the 6 underway.  And while I fully recognize that Civil War movie was WAY different from the comics, SpiderMan was already an established hero by the time that story rolled around and he got roped in and SCREWED by Stark.   This SpiderMan seems weaker by comparison, SpiderMan does not take unmasked lectures from other heroes, he tells'em to stick it and keep doin his thing.  Does the suit make the man, we all already know the answer, but I don't feel like the question should have ever been asked. Still gonna see it, I'm a sucker for SpiderMan.

Stark: "Do me a favor, can't you just be a friendly neighborhood spiderman?" Peter: "No ned, no"  Ned: "Do you know him too?" (Capt. America) Peter: (whispers) "Stole his shield."  Ned: "Can i try the suit on?" Peter: *Nods* Ned: " Du Duuuuu" (Humming)  Flying monster guy: "The rich and the powerful, like stark. They don't care about us" Flying monster guy: " The worlds changing boys, time we change too."  Peter: "These weapons are *crazy* dangerous"  Stark: "Listen Peter, forget the flying monster guy." Stark: "There are people who handle that sort of thing."  Peter: "Your legal weapons barrier was at 2:30, ya missed it" Peter: "No no no no" Peter: *screams*  Stark: "What if someone would have died?" Peter: "I was just trying to be like you" Stark: "I want you to be better, I'm gonna need that suit back" Peter: "But I'm nothing without this suit!"  Stark: "If you're nothing without that suit, then you shouldn't have it"  Peter: "I screwed up"  Aunt may: "You need to stop carrying the weight of the world on your shoulders"  Flying monster guy: "I want you to understand, I'll do anything to protect my family" Flying monster guy: "I know you know what I'm talking about." Flying monster guy: "So don't mess with me, cause I will kill you and everybody you love."  Girl: "My friend is up there!"  Peter: "The guy is still out there, I just gotta do this on my own"  Stark: "Just don't do anything stupid." Peter: *On a crashing plane* "I got this" Stark: "Alright?" text: My friend said:    "Hey, I saw you added me in the creators thing at the end and I have an idea for iron man (since it's next time) The creators say that captain America could beat iron man in hand on hand combat, but yet he beat ultron hand on hand which Thor could not even defeat hand on his hammer, so I was thinking...   Iron man the secret goddess of marvel?!?"  And I thought...  "Ok, that seems reasonable... but what about Spider-Man? He has about 1 million times his strength of his own body and can stop a speeding train. And if he can throw Rhino all the way across the block without a super powered suit and can survive fighting Captain America, (in civil war, which he won, but cap made him hold a falling plane just to stall a get-away) then would he be the secret goddess? And Iron Man created Ultron, so he knows him by heart. Which means... Spider Man the secret Goddess of Marvel?!?"  What do you guys think?

text: How is it that Thor: Ragnorak has 35 mil views in just a few weeks and yet this has 5 mil in over a month? Is it because of the former has a catchy song? The Defender's Trailer came out yesterday and it has 4.25 mil views. I really hope that there are going to be more TV spots soon. I don't want an over-saturation with a dozen TV spots, 3 trailers, and a character bio that tells everything we need to know; I just want more love for Spidey. All I'm saying is that it's two months until release and we only have 2 trailers for the movie. I just hope that Sony isn't doing any foul (fowl) play here in terms of distribution in an attempt to sink the film before it's released. I really hope that this is all a plan from Marvel to not reveal too much about the film too early like what happened with ASM2.

text: SPIDERMAN-HOMECOMING ! I love this hero so much you all do not even know. I grew up with Spider-Man ever since I could remember. I would buy his toys, his masks, dress up as him, pretend to be him, watch his tv shows, sing his theme songs etc. As a kid I thought he was the most awesome guy ever. The wat he swings, fights, talks, and acts all seemed so incredible, and the life that he lives always interested me. I could never explai. Why honestly. It wansnt just the amazing and awesome city that he lived in, or his super powers, his bravery, his courage, his will, care for others, and so on. Well....I guess it is. But it us the fact he is so relatable and you are able to connect with him, especially as a kid. He is a dude that is living a normal life besides the Super Hero stuff. He is a kid, goes to school, faces family and friend issues, does homework, studies, explores, and has fun. He is just a normal guy. That is what I love about him, he is like us. He proves, besides the super powers, that anybody, no matter what age can be a hero to protect the city, family, friends, and home that he loves. His battles mentally and physically have always inspired me, and still do to this age. No words can describe how much I love Spider-Man, and how excited I am for this film. This is one of my most hyped up films ever! Everytime I struggled as a kid, I would look at him, out myself in his shoes, and become Spider-Man. The reason why I was able to find it is because Spider-Man lives inside of me. He lives inside if all of us. I said it before and I will say it again.....SPIDER-MAN IS THE GREATEST SUPERHERO EVER! Tom is perfect for Spider-Man! He will join the likes of RDJ, Ryan Reynolds, and Hugh Jackman for the best Superhero castings of all time. This is the Spider-Man we want! I CANNOT WAIT FOR THIS FILM AS A SPIDER-MAN/COMIC BOOK FAN AND A MOVIE FAN! CANNOT WAIT! AUDIENCE AND CRITICS ARE LOVING THIS MOVIE! I cannot believe it is this good! I knew it I frickin told everyone this was going to make history and be the best Spider-Man ever! I TOLD ALL OF YOU! Now go get ready, put your clothes, get hyped, go to a theater, and buy tickets to the best Spider-Man you have ever seen. LEGENDARY!🐜🐜🐜🐜🐜👏👏😱😱👑👑👑😭😭😭💪💪❤💙! THIS GOT ME EVEN MORE HYPED! ANOTHER DAMN HIT! SPIDER-MAN HOMECOMING JUST MADE HISTORY!👑👑👑

text: I JUST SPIDERMAN-HOMECOMING! I ADORED IT! I loved this film so much I cannot describe it. I was crying with tears of joy, and had a big and young smile on my face througout the whole film! It was just incredible and this movie means a lot to me. I love this hero so much you all do not even know. I grew up with Spider-Man ever since I could remember. I would buy his toys, his masks, dress up as him, pretend to be him, watch his tv shows, sing his theme songs etc. As a kid I thought he was the most awesome guy ever. The wat he swings, fights, talks, and acts all seemed so incredible, and the life that he lives always interested me. I could never explai. Why honestly. It wansnt just the amazing and awesome city that he lived in, or his super powers, his bravery, his courage, his will, care for others, and so on. Well....I guess it is. But it us the fact he is so relatable and you are able to connect with him, especially as a kid. He is a dude that is living a normal life besides the Super Hero stuff. He is a kid, goes to school, faces family and friend issues, does homework, studies, explores, and has fun. He is just a normal guy. That is what I love about him, he is like us. He proves, besides the super powers, that anybody, no matter what age can be a hero to protect the city, family, friends, and home that he loves. His battles mentally and physically have always inspired me, and still do to this age. No words can describe how much I love Spider-Man, and how happy I am. This is one of my most hyped up films ever! Everytime I struggled as a kid, I would look at him, out myself in his shoes, and become Spider-Man. The reason why I was able to find it is because Spider-Man lives inside of me. He lives inside if all of us. I said it before and I will say it again.....SPIDER-MAN IS THE GREATEST SUPERHERO EVER! Tom is perfect for Spider-Man! He will join the likes of RDJ, Ryan Reynolds, and Hugh Jackman for the best Superhero castings of all time. This is the Spider-Man we want! This film was amazing and is a great to every Comic Book and even movie can put there. Finally after so long they got it right, and thank the lord Sony gave the rights back to Marvel! Let's start off with the actors. THEY WERE ALL GREAT...most of them. What can I say about Tom Holland that I along with everyone have not said already! HE IS INCREDIBLE AS SPIDEY! Not only is he incredible, but he is the best Spider-Man ever, and the best Spider-Man we will ever have. The way he talks, his emotions, his life, his age, his humor, his wittyness, his passion, live, care, and the way he acts is just perfect! He really shows how he was destined to be Spider-Man and Peter Parker! He has some emotional scenes that were done extremely well, but where he shines is his childlike behavior. For so long we have gotten Super Heros that hate their powers and life, and see them as a burden they have to carry. It is so nice and fresh to finally have someone who is happy and excited with their powers! Let's be honest, if we found out we had super powers, we would go crazy. And that is exactly what happens to him! Peter/Tom/Spidey go nuts about his powers, and he gets so anxious, happy, excited, and yes even childish with them! Exactly how Spider-Man should be, especially considering that he is a young kid. They play it realistically, which makes him even more relatable. He is immature and young with his powers, so everything is a thrill ride and learning experience for him, and to watch that is just amazing. And yeah he messed up.......in so many ways😂😂But that is hilarious and sad to watch, and it is done extremely well. Peter along with the other kids of the film....act like kids! It was great to see! It is like going to a regular High School and going through your day. It seems real and relatable. They act like young kids going through their daily lives and that was so satisfying to see. Tom Holland is spectacular as Spider-Man and Peter Parker! I said it from the begining, HE IS THE BEST SPIDER-MAN EVER! Zendaya was great in this film! She was not in it too much, but she delivered extremely well. She was hilarious and added something unique to the film. She added mystery, humor, and something else I cannot put my finger on....BUT I LOVED HER! Michael Ketton was awesome in this! I loved his motivation and how interesting he was. He is soooooo menacing! You understand where he is coming from, but he scares the shit out of you😂 Michael was awesome as Vulture! Marisa Tomei is great as Aunt May! She cares for Peter so much, and she emotionally grips you with her love for Peter. She is funny, charming, caring, attractive and extremely protective. She is perfect for Aunt May and her scenes with Peter are great! Jacob Batalon was great as Peter's best friend! He was hilarious and made everyone in the audience laugh! Tony Revolori was a different Flash, but he was good. Not in it for too long, but he was good. And Robert Downey Jr....you all knew he was going to be great like come on he never faiis as Tony. He is a mentor and Father Figure for Peter, even though he is not "the best" at it. He is still a little bit of a sick to Peter, but you can tell he cares so much about him. He shows up when he messes up and tries to set him straight. His scenes with Peter are amazing to watch and it feels so real and capturing. It feels like a father is setting his son straight. That is their relationship, Father and son. RBJ/Tony was great in this film. He is not in it for that long, and you see more Tony Stark than Iron Man, but he delivers as always. Now he is a negative. Luara Harrier is not bad in the film, but she seems so forced and randomly placed their. I feel she serves no real purpse in the film and that she was just placed their for a love story. I was not a fan of the romance, but I understood it and appreciated it is that makes sense.       The action was superb and had an exciting atmosphere that created a very fun and crazy tone. The style of action and fighting really brought another mostly fresh take and door opening to the MCU. A lot of exolosions, alien guns, missles, , web slinging, punching, hard hits, and more was included in the film, and man was it awesome! I have always loved the way Spider-Man fights. To see him beating up bad guys, swinging from building, flipping, and so on was just thrilling! The action scenes were fantastic and the way their were filmed and choreographed was amazing. Loved the action! The movie looks splendid and solid too. You really feel like you are in New York City with him swinging or walking around. All the set pieces and locations they picked were spot on and incredible. The action was what I like to call "Spider-Man" action, which is the most or some of the most unique Comic Book action and action in general you will ever see. Every action sequence felt real yet Comic Book like. This movie is ridiculously fun, like I mean this is one of the most fun and entertaining films in a long time or ever! I had a blast watching this film, to the point where my be in exploded (not really but it felt like it did)! I was incredibly entertained watching this movie! And my God is this film hilrious!? THE WHOLE AUDIENCE WAS DYING FROM LAUGHTER EVERY SECOND! I was not able to breathe! It is incredibly funny, charming, witty, clever, and unexpected! Every joke landed for me, and that last scene.....THAT LAST SCENE😂😂😂😂😂IT WAS SO UNEXPECTED AND CLEVER! It shocked the packed auditorium, but we alI died of laughter. I have not laughed that hard in a long time! That is one of my favorite movie endings for a Comic Book movie ever, or movie ever. AMAZING! And also note that my audience was gasping at certain parts! Their is a moment in the film that is so unexpected and shocking, THE WHOLE AUDEIENCE GASPED AND WAS TALKING! I heard a few people say something like "OH SHIT"!I LOVE THAT SCENE! Seriously like I am going to remember that moment because of the atmosphere, reaction, and scene. It was so tense!       All in all, I FRICKIN LOVED SPIDER-MAN:HOMECOMING! It is one of my favorite comic movies ever and one of my favorite movies in a long time. I recommend everyone to go check this movie out, if you weren't going to already for some reason😕. If your a comic book fan or movie fan, this movie will blow your hearts away and satisfy you. A great film that anyone can love. Great Job to the cast of Spider-Man:Homecoming for the great marketing, promoting, interviews, merchandise, hype, and overall great movie. Thank you Marvel for giving out another hit and saving Spider-Man! This is one of the best Comic Book movies ever, the best film of the summer so far, and the best Comic Book movies in years. The perfect Spider-Man movie, and damn near a perfect film! Incredible, amazing...SPECTACULAR! 9/10 to a 9.5/10👍😉😱💙❤✈✈👑👑🚇🚒🚈🚓🚕🚗🚗🚘🚚🚌🚎🚖🚖🚖🚐🚍🚇🚇🚐🚠🏠🏨🏢🏣🏤🏥🏦🏫🏫🏪🏩🏨🏧🏧💼🎒📚📙📘📗📓📑📛📰📚🐜🐜🐜🐜🐜🐜🐜🐜🐜💥🔥👑👑👑👑

text: There's now officially (not at all officially, more like just-my-opinion-ally) twice as many good Spider-Man movies as there is bad ones. But _Homecoming_ is my favourite of the bunch. 2017 has been a great year for the Superhero genre, and _Spider-Man: Homecoming_ does nothing to buck that trend. It's got everything a Spider-Man movie should have: Heart, humour, action, spectacle, a grounded school life, coming-of-age themes, and all this while firmly rooting itself in the Marvel Cinematic Universe -- without relying on the framework of the past to hold it up. _Spider-Man: Homecoming_ is spectacular, and it stands up both on its own, and as a part of the larger universe. _Final rating:★★★½ - I really liked it. text: BEST and my personal favorite Peter Parker (Spider-man) to date.  BEST cast chemistry of all the MCU films combined.  I get what people mean when they call this version of Spider-man "Iron Man Jr", but there is a line in the film where Peter says, "Mr. Stark really overdid it" referring to all the gadgets in his suit. THAT confirms to me that Peter is trying his best to prove himself and become more independent.  Do you know what that's called? Character development.  Tom Holland's Peter Parker is still a kid. He has a lot to learn in order to grow as a character. I'm excited as a viewer to accompany him on his journey.
